to Singapore?</p><p data-renderer-start-pos="497">But youâ€™re unsure if a <strong data-renderer-mark="true">representative office</strong> is the right choice.</p><p data-renderer-start-pos="564">Unlike a subsidiary or branch, a representative office has strict limitationsâ€”it canâ€™t generate revenue or engage in commercial activities.</p><p data-renderer-start-pos="705">So, when does it make sense to set one up? And what are the key factors to consider?</p><p data-renderer-start-pos="791">In this guide, youâ€™ll get <strong data-renderer-mark="true">expert insights</strong> on whether a representative office is the right fit for your business, along with its benefits, restrictions, and alternatives.</p><p data-renderer-start-pos="962">Letâ€™s dive in.</p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="what-is-a-representative-office-in-singapore" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">1.</span> <span class="heading_text">What is a representative office in Singapore?</span></h2><p>A representative office, or a RO, is <strong>a temporary business setup for foreign companies exploring opportunities in Singapore without engaging in commercial activities.</strong></p><p>In other words, you can think of a RO as a research and relationship-building hub.</p><p>An RO allows you to study the market, build connections, and promote your brandâ€”but it canâ€™t generate revenue, sign contracts, or offer services.</p><p>For example, a multinational corporation set up an RO in Singapore to conduct market research on how normal consumer prefers vegan meat or not, which types of products are potential before fully entering the region.Â </p><p>Since itâ€™s not a legal entity, an RO has strict limitations but serves as a low-risk way to establish a presence in Singapore</p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="what-are-the-differences-between-a-representative-office-and-a-branch-office" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">2.</span> <span class="heading_text">What are the differences between a Representative office and a branch office?</span></h2><p>A representative office is not the only way for entering the Singapore market, a foreign company can choose to <a href="branch-office.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">open a branch office</a>, a RO, to set a foothold in the Lion City.</p><p>When considering options, itâ€™s crucial to understand the differences between a representative office and a branch office.</p><p>While both serve as an extension of a foreign parent company (the parent company is fully liable for the entity), the key distinction<strong> lies in their allowed actitivites.</strong></p><p>If your goal is to test the market before committing, an RO is a low-risk option. If you want to do business and generate revenue, a branch office is the better choice.</p><table border="1" style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100.03%; height: 121.208px;"><colgroup><col style="width: 33.2942%;"><col style="width: 33.2942%;"><col style="width: 33.2942%;"></colgroup> <thead> <tr style="height: 52.8021px;"> <td style="height: 52.8021px;"><span>Feature</span></td> <td style="height: 52.8021px;"><span>Representative office</span></td> <td colorname="" style="height: 52.8021px;"><p data-renderer-start-pos="2522">Branch office</p></td> </tr> </thead> <tbody> <tr style="height: 20.8021px;"> <td style="height: 20.8021px;"><span>Purpose</span></td> <td style="height: 20.8021px;"><span>Market research, liaison activities</span></td> <td style="height: 20.8021px;"><span>Revenue-generating business operations</span></td> </tr> <tr style="height: 26.8021px;"> <td style="height: 26.8021px;"><span>Allowed activities</span></td> <td style="height: 26.8021px;"><span>Non-commercial (research, promotion)</span></td> <td style="height: 26.8021px;"><span>Commercial (sales, contracts, operations)</span></td> </tr> <tr style="height: 20.8021px;"> <td style="height: 20.8021px;"><span>Taxation</span></td> <td style="height: 20.8021px;"><span>Not taxable (No revenue)</span></td> <td style="height: 20.8021px;"><span>Taxed as a non-resident entity</span></td> </tr> </tbody> </table><p></p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="why-so-many-international-companies-choose-to-register-a-representative-office-in-singapore" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">3.</span> <span class="heading_text">Why so many international companies choose to register a representative office in Singapore?</span></h2><p>A Representative Office (RO) is a low-risk, cost-effective way for major international businesses to explore the Singapore market.Â </p><p>Hereâ€™s why global companies choose this route:</p><div data-rlta-element="container" data-rlta-state="initial" data-rlta-id="1" data-rlta-type="accordions" data-rlta-title-tag="div" data-rlta-orientation="vertical" data-rlta-wrap-buttons="false" data-rlta-remember-active="false" data-rlta-theme="neutral" data-rlta-color-panels="false" data-rlta-positioning="top" data-rlta-alignment="left" data-rlta-has-button-scroller="false"><div id="rlta-1-minimal-setup-costs" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-1-minimal-setup-costs" aria-expanded="true" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="1-minimal-setup-costs" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="open"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 1. Minimal setup costs</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-1-minimal-setup-costs" aria-labelledby="rlta-1-minimal-setup-costs" tabindex="-1" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="open" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>An RO is cheaper to establish for major corporations. With no corporate taxes and fewer compliance requirements, itâ€™s an affordable way to gain a foothold.Â </p><p>However, for smaller companies or SMEs, a RO is not ideal as the minimum requirements is hard to meet.</p></div></div><div id="rlta-title-2-market-exploration-without-commitment" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-title-2-market-exploration-without-commitment" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="title-2-market-exploration-without-commitment" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> title="2. Market exploration without commitment</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-title-2-market-exploration-without-commitment" aria-labelledby="rlta-title-2-market-exploration-without-commitment" tabindex="-1" hidden="true" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="closed" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>Businesses use ROs to study market trends, understand customer needs, and assess business potentialâ€”before making a full investment.</p></div></div><div id="rlta-3-brand-presence-networking" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-3-brand-presence-networking" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="3-brand-presence-networking" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 3. Brand Presence &amp; Networking</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-3-brand-presence-networking" aria-labelledby="rlta-3-brand-presence-networking" tabindex="-1" hidden="true" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="closed" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>While an RO canâ€™t generate revenue, it allows companies to build connections with local partners, suppliers, and industry players.Â </p></div></div><div id="rlta-4-easy-transition-to-a-legal-entity" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-4-easy-transition-to-a-legal-entity" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="4-easy-transition-to-a-legal-entity" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 4. Easy transition to a legal entity</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-4-easy-transition-to-a-legal-entity" aria-labelledby="rlta-4-easy-transition-to-a-legal-entity" tabindex="-1" hidden="true" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="closed" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>Once the company is ready, it can convert the RO into a subsidiary or branch office to start operations officially.</p><p>For companies considering expansion, an RO is an ideal first step before making long-term commitments.</p></div></div></div><h2 class="indexed"><span id="what-are-the-limitations-of-a-representative-office" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">4.</span> <span class="heading_text">What are the limitations of a representative office?</span></h2><p>While an RO offers a strategic entry point, it comes with strict restrictions:</p><div data-rlta-element="container" data-rlta-state="initial" data-rlta-id="2" data-rlta-type="accordions" data-rlta-title-tag="div" data-rlta-orientation="vertical" data-rlta-wrap-buttons="false" data-rlta-remember-active="false" data-rlta-theme="neutral" data-rlta-color-panels="false" data-rlta-positioning="top" data-rlta-alignment="left" data-rlta-has-button-scroller="false"><div id="rlta-1-no-revenue-generation" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-1-no-revenue-generation" aria-expanded="true" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="1-no-revenue-generation" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="open"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 1. No revenue generation</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-1-no-revenue-generation" aria-labelledby="rlta-1-no-revenue-generation" tabindex="-1" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="open" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>An RO cannot sell products, sign contracts, or engage in commercial activitiesâ€”limiting its direct business impact</p></div></div><div id="rlta-2-temporary-status" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-2-temporary-status" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="2-temporary-status" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 2. Temporary status</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-2-temporary-status" aria-labelledby="rlta-2-temporary-status" tabindex="-1" hidden="true" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="closed" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>ROs are only valid for up to three years, after which they must transition into a legal entity or cease operations.</p></div></div><div id="rlta-3-liability-on-parent-xompany" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-3-liability-on-parent-xompany" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" data-rlta-alias="3-liability-on-parent-xompany" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 3. Liability on parent xompany</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-3-liability-on-parent-xompany" aria-labelledby="rlta-3-liability-on-parent-xompany" tabindex="-1" hidden="true" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="closed" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>Since an RO isnâ€™t a separate entity, the parent company is fully responsible for its obligations.</p><p>If your goal is to actively do business in Singapore, an RO may not be the right fitâ€”a subsidiary or branch office would be a better option.</p></div></div></div><h3 class="indexed"><span id="how-to-set-up-a-representative-office-in-singapore" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">4.1.</span> <span class="heading_text">How to set up a representative office in Singapore?</span></h3><p>Setting up a ROs in Singapore is a straightforward process with ACRA and Enterprise Singapore, but you must meet specific eligibility criteria and provide the required documents.</p><h3 class="indexed"><span id="eligibility-criteria-and-required-documents" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">4.2.</span> <span class="heading_text">Eligibility criteria and required documents</span></h3><p>To qualify for an RO, the foreign company must:</p><ul> <li>Have a sales turnover of more than US$250,000;</li> <li>Be established for at least three years;</li> <li>Intend to employ fewer than five staff members in the RO.</li> </ul><p>Additionally, the company must have a CorpPass account before applying. If the foreign companies have no CorpPass account, they should engage a registered agent (service provider) like Global Link Asia Consulting to make the RO application</p><p>The requirement documents in official English translations include</p><ol> <li>Softcopy of Certificate of Incorporation (or Registration Certificate of the parent company);</li> <li>Softcopy of the latest Audited Accounts of the foreign company;</li> <li>Official letterhead to state the purpose of the RO and the conducting activities in Singapore. (with a signature by the Parent Organization Authorized Personnel).</li> </ol><p>To submit the final application, you must make a non-refundable processing fee of S$200 per year. Payment can be made via Credit/Debit Cards.</p><h3 class="indexed"><span id="step-by-step-process-to-register-a-representative-office" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">4.3.</span> <span class="heading_text">Step-by-step process to register a representative office</span></h3><p><ul class="nav nav-pills mb-3 nav-quy-trinh acm-quytrinh-article style-2 " role="tablist" id="acm-mod-1514"> <li class="nav-item"> <a class="active" data-toggle="pill" href="#" data-target="#article-1514-1" role="tab" aria-selected="true"><div><span>1</span></div></a> <p>Step 1: Understand your needs </p></li> <li class="nav-item"> <a class="" data-toggle="pill" href="#" data-target="#article-1514-2" role="tab" aria-selected="false"><div><span>2</span></div></a> <p>Step 2: Confirm fees and agreements </p></li> <li class="nav-item"> <a class="" data-toggle="pill" href="#" data-target="#article-1514-3" role="tab" aria-selected="false"><div><span>3</span></div></a> <p>Step 3: Prepare documents </p></li> <li class="nav-item"> <a class="" data-toggle="pill" href="#" data-target="#article-1514-4" role="tab" aria-selected="false"><div><span>4</span></div></a> <p>Step 4: Submit Registration </p></li> <li class="nav-item"> <a class="" data-toggle="pill" href="#" data-target="#article-1514-5" role="tab" aria-selected="false"><div><span>5</span></div></a> <p>Step 5: Obtain Work Pass & Open a Bank Account </p></li> </ul><div class="tab-content content-quy-trinh"><div class="tab-pane fade active show" id="article-1514-1" role="tabpanel"><p>If you decide to open a ROs in Singapore, you can contact Global Link Asia Consulting via email or visit the office directly for direct consultation.</p></div><div class="tab-pane fade " id="article-1514-2" role="tabpanel"><p>We provide detailed information and fees via email. Once both parties agree, you need to make payment and follow the instructions provided.</p></div><div class="tab-pane fade " id="article-1514-3" role="tabpanel"><p>Our experts assist in preparing and submitting required documents, including:</p><ul> <li>Parent company details (business license, last 3 years' financial reports, latest financial statements)</li> <li>Representativeâ€™s information and passport copy (valid for at least 6 months)</li> <li>Application for an Employment Pass (if needed)</li> </ul> </div><div class="tab-pane fade " id="article-1514-4" role="tabpanel"><p>We apply ACRA and Enterprise Singapore. Approval takes 3â€“10 days, but may take longer if additional verification is required.</p></div><div class="tab-pane fade " id="article-1514-5" role="tabpanel"><p>After approval, we will help you apply for the Employment Pass with the Ministry of Manpower (MOM). Once approved, the representative can work in Singapore. If needed, GLA also assists in opening a corporate bank account.</p></div></div></p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="what-to-do-after-opening-your-representative-office-in-singapore" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">5.</span> <span class="heading_text">What to do after opening your representative office in Singapore?</span></h2><p>Setting up your representative office is just the first step. To ensure compliance, hereâ€™s what you need to do next:</p><h3 class="indexed"><span id="operational-timeline-and-renewal" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">5.1.</span> <span class="heading_text">Operational timeline and renewal</span></h3><p>An RO can operate in Singapore for a maximum of three years.</p><ul> <li>It must be renewed annually to continue operations.</li> <li>After three years, the company must consider converting to a Branch Office, Private Limited (Pte. Ltd.), or a Partnership to maintain its presence.</li> <li>In order to register a subsidiary company or a branch office, Singapore requires foreign companies to engage the services of a registered filing agent.</li> </ul><p>If you need assistance, you can always contact us today</p><h3 class="indexed"><span id="tax-legal-compliance" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">5.2.</span> <span class="heading_text">Tax &amp; legal compliance</span></h3><p>An RO is not considered a separate legal entity, so it isnâ€™t required to pay taxes or submit annual financial reports.</p><p>However, it must comply with Singaporeâ€™s labor laws and employee insurance regulations for its staff.</p><p>Reporting &amp; disclosure requirements</p><p>All official documents must clearly state: â€œRegistered Representative Office in Singapore.â€<br>The RO must notify Enterprise Singapore (IE) within one month of any changes in:</p><ol> <li>Â Office address;</li> <li>Phone number;</li> <li>Fax number.</li> </ol><p>If the RO closes or transitions into a branch/subsidiary, it must inform Enterprise Singapore within one month.</p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="understanding-the-role-of-the-accounting-and-corporate-regulatory-authority" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">6.</span> <span class="heading_text">Understanding the role of the Accounting and Corporate Regulatory Authority</span></h2><p>The Accounting and Corporate Regulatory Authority (ACRA) plays a crucial role in overseeing the registration and operation of representative offices in Singapore.</p><p>They ensure that all foreign entities comply with local laws and regulations, maintaining a transparent business environment.</p><p>ACRA also monitors the activities of representative offices to ensure they operate within the confines of the law, focusing solely on non-commercial activities such as market research and client communication.</p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="understanding-the-role-of-enterprise-singapore" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">7.</span> <span class="heading_text">Understanding the role of Enterprise Singapore</span></h2><p>Enterprise Singapore plays a vital role in supporting foreign companies looking to enter the local market. They offer various resources, including market insights, networking opportunities, and funding support.Â </p><p>However, understanding how to leverage these resources effectively can be challenging for foreign companies.</p><p>Engaging with Enterprise Singapore early in the process can provide valuable guidance and support, helping you navigate the complexities of setting up a representative office in Singapore.</p><p>Their expertise can significantly enhance your understanding of the local business environment and help you make the most of your presence in Singapore.</p><h2 class="indexed"><span id="how-can-we-help-you-with-your-ro-registration" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">8.</span> <span class="heading_text">How can we help you with your RO registration?</span></h2><p>Establishing a Representative Office (RO) in Singapore is a straightforward way to explore new opportunities</p><ol> <li>But opening an RO is just the beginning. To make the most of your presence in Singapore, you need toÂ </li> <li>Stay compliant with renewal reporting requirements</li> <li>Plan for the future â€”whether that means transitioning into a Branch Office or Private Limited (Pte. Ltd.)</li> </ol><p>The best approach? Use your RO strategically to build connections, test the market, and lay the groundwork for long-term business expansion. And when you need support, you can count on the experts of Global Link Asia Consulting to build your sustainable business expansion</p><p>We can help you</p><ul> <li><a href="../../../company-incorporation/singapore.html">Register a company in Singapore;</a></li> <li><a href="../../../open-a-bank-account/bank-account-opening-in-singapore.html">Open a corporate bank account in Singapore</a> with a 99% success rate;</li> <li>Choose the right company types for tax optimization in Singapore;</li> <li>Apply for Singapore business licenses;</li> <li>Get an affordable, professional <a href="../../../a-to-z-service/business-address.html">registered office address for business</a>;</li> <li>Support to open, authenticate, and manageÂ <a href="../../../a-to-z-service/payment-solutions.html">Stripe Paypal Business in Singapore, Hong Kong, and the U.S</a>;</li> <li><a href="../../../tax-accounting/tax-accounting-in-singapore.html">Handle all your tax accounting needs, timely annual filings, auditing, and more</a>.</li> </ul><h2 class="indexed"><span id="faqs-about-singapore-company-types" class="anchor"></span><span class="heading_number">9.</span> <span class="heading_text">FAQs about Singapore company types</span></h2><div data-rlta-element="container" data-rlta-state="initial" data-rlta-id="3" data-rlta-type="accordions" data-rlta-title-tag="div" data-rlta-orientation="vertical" data-rlta-wrap-buttons="false" data-rlta-remember-active="false" data-rlta-theme="neutral" data-rlta-color-panels="false" data-rlta-positioning="top" data-rlta-alignment="left" data-rlta-has-button-scroller="false"><div id="rlta-1-what-exactly-can-a-representative-office-do" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-1-what-exactly-can-a-representative-office-do" aria-expanded="true" tabindex="0" class="icon-faq" data-rlta-alias="1-what-exactly-can-a-representative-office-do" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="open"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 1. What exactly can a representative office do?</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-1-what-exactly-can-a-representative-office-do" aria-labelledby="rlta-1-what-exactly-can-a-representative-office-do" tabindex="-1" class="icon-faq" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="open" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>The functions of a representative office are pretty specific. It can conduct market research, promote the parent companyâ€™s products, and liaise with clients.</p></div></div><div id="rlta-2-how-does-a-representative-office-differ-from-an-office-or-a-branch-office" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-2-how-does-a-representative-office-differ-from-an-office-or-a-branch-office" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" class="icon-faq" data-rlta-alias="2-how-does-a-representative-office-differ-from-an-office-or-a-branch-office" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 2. How does a representative office differ from an office or a branch office?</div></div><div id="rlta-panel-2-how-does-a-representative-office-differ-from-an-office-or-a-branch-office" aria-labelledby="rlta-2-how-does-a-representative-office-differ-from-an-office-or-a-branch-office" tabindex="-1" class="icon-faq" hidden="true" data-rlta-element="panel" data-rlta-state="closed" data-rlta-color="false"><div data-rlta-element="panel-content"><p>A representative office is mainly for non-commercial activities and cannot generate income, while a branch office can engage in business activities and is considered a permanent establishment.</p><p>So, if you want to set up a permanent establishment, a branch office is the way to go!</p></div></div><div id="rlta-3-who-usually-heads-a-representative-office" role="button" aria-controls="rlta-panel-3-who-usually-heads-a-representative-office" aria-expanded="false" tabindex="0" class="icon-faq" data-rlta-alias="3-who-usually-heads-a-representative-office" data-rlta-element="button" data-rlta-state="closed"><div data-rlta-element="heading"> 